title: For Sale:  Early 1899 Savage Lever Action Carbine Takedown in .22 HP
postcontent:
Hello,
I have a model 99 Savage lever action take-down rifle in great condition.  It has an 18" barrel, and is chambered in .22 HP,  which is still readily available at most gun shops as 5.6X52mm (it's european designation).  
The rifle is in good condition for it's age, with much of the bluing  present, but also with some blemishes (nice patina).  I believe the furniture is original and in fantastic condition, although the butt plate has been replaced. The bolt is jeweled and beautiful, and the trigger & sear were polished and accurized.  The action is quite unique on these rifles, and very robust.  There is a brass rotary magazine that holds 3, with a really neat window in the side of the receiver that shows how many rounds are left.  The Rifle was made around 1912 or 1913, judging by the serial number.  The rifling looks bright and crisp.  The lever action operates and the rifle shoots well and it quite accurate.  It also has some period extras, like  flip-up Marbles sights and a Lyman peep sight.  

The rifle also is a takedown model, so it can be broken down into three components with no tools, the longest part being 20" long.  The joint between the barrel and receiver locks up very tight, with no play when assembled.

The .22 HP round is still quite popular in Europe, and is one of the first high-power .22's on the market in the early 1900's.  Ballistically it is superior to the .223 Remington, but less than the 22-250.  In the early days of the HP, some almost magical shot results with large game were reported, making the new round the perfect dangerous game round.  Then some hunters were eaten by their wounded quarry, and the round fell out of favor in the US.  Around the same time, some higher performance .22 caliber rounds hit the market domestically.  But the round continues to be popular in Europe, and is quite effective for game up to deer size (although keep in mind that  currently .22 caliber, no matter what the power, is not legal to hunt deer with in WA State). 

Out of state shipping is available.  For local sales, I also have about a half box of commercial ammo, and some spent brass.

For a 100+ year old rifle, it is in wonderful condition, and it ready for your collection or next hunt!

Price is firm, and I am not interested in any trades at this time.  

Thanks for looking, and have a good day.

If you've ever wanted an HK93 5.56, but have never wanted to spend almost $4k on one, this is the closest you'll get for a fraction of the cost.
